apeutic use</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000008" MajorTopicYN="N">administration &amp; dosage</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008297" MajorTopicYN="N">Male</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D011743" MajorTopicYN="Y">Pyrimidines</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000009" MajorTopicYN="N">adverse effects</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000627" MajorTopicYN="N">therapeutic use</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000008" MajorTopicYN="N">administration &amp; dosage</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D011759" MajorTopicYN="Y">Pyrrolidines</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000009" MajorTopicYN="N">adverse effects</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000627" MajorTopicYN="N">therapeutic use</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000008" MajorTopicYN="N">administration &amp; dosage</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D005260" MajorTopicYN="N">Female</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008875" MajorTopicYN="N">Middle Aged</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D013449" MajorTopicYN="Y">Sulfonamides</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000009" MajorTopicYN="N">adverse effects</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000627" MajorTopicYN="N">therapeutic use</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000008" MajorTopicYN="N">administration &amp; dosage</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000075242" MajorTopicYN="Y">Janus Kinase Inhibitors</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000009" MajorTopicYN="N">adverse effects</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000627" MajorTopicYN="N">therapeutic use</QualifierName><QualifierName UI="Q000008" MajorTopicYN="N">administration &amp; dosage</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000368" MajorTopicYN="N">Aged</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D016896" MajorTopicYN="N">Treatment Outcome</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000096926" MajorTopicYN="N">Benzenesulfonamides</DescriptorName></MeshHeading></MeshHeadingList><OtherAbstract Type="plain-language-summary" Language="eng"><AbstractText><b>What is this article about?</b>Myelofibrosis is a rare type of bone marrow cancer that disrupts the body&#x2019;s normal blood cell production. People who have myelofibrosis often feel tired, weak, and feverish, and may bruise or bleed easily and have pain on their left side due to an enlarged spleen. Treatment for myelofibrosis typically involves medications known as JAK inhibitors, which have been shown to be effective in reducing spleen size and improving symptoms, including discomfort associated with an enlarged spleen. There are four approved JAK inhibitors available for treating myelofibrosis in the US: momelotinib, pacritinib, fedratinib, and ruxolitinib. There are some differences in side effects among these JAK inhibitors, but there are not always clinical trials available that directly compare these JAK inhibitors to each other. In this study, we used an indirect comparison method to evaluate the side effects of momelotinib and fedratinib.<b>What were the results?</b>The findings show that momelotinib was associated with a lower risk of several side effects, including anemia (too few red blood cells), diarrhea, and nausea.<b>What do the results of the study mean?</b>These results suggest momelotinib may offer a more tolerable treatment for people with myelofibrosis.</AbstractText></OtherAbstract><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">JAK inhibitor</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Myelofibrosis</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">fedratinib</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">indirect treatment comparison</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">momelotinib</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">safety</Keyword></KeywordList><CoiStatement>Lucia Masarova reports advisory board participation with MorphoSys. Srdan Verstovsek reports consulting fees f